article.description: Katie Smith scored 30 points, including a career high-tying seven 3-pointers, to lead the Detroit Shock to their sixth straight victory, 84-70 over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.
article.headline: Smith's 30 points, career high-tying seven 3s lead Shock
article.linkText: Smith's 30 pace Shock's dismantling of Monarchs
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Under strict orders by the Detroit Shock coaching staff to shoot more, Katie Smith is making opponents wish she would return to a more pass-first mentality.

Smith scored 30 points, including a career high-tying seven 3-pointers, to lead the Shock to their sixth straight victory, 84-70 over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.

It's been another fast start for Detroit (7-1), which has the WNBA's top record. The Shock began last year with a franchise-best 10-1 record before losing the next game to the Monarchs at Arco Arena.

The shooting of Smith, who has moved from point guard to small forward this year, has been critical to Detroit's success. Despite missing 19 of 22 shots over the first three games, Smith was was told by coach Bill Laimbeer to start being more aggressive.

"It's a mind-set, being aggressive," said Smith, who made 7-of-12 3-pointers against the Monarchs. "I'm not going to get 30 points every night, but it's about making the defense work. My shot feels good right now, hopefully I can keep shooting with the best of them."

Smith scored 33 points in a victory over Seattle on Wednesday and came out strong against the Monarchs as well. Shooting primarily from the perimeter, the veteran star was 11-for-21 from the field, and her seven 3s tied a franchise record and was one short of Diana Taurasi's WNBA record.

Deanna Nolan was the other major force offensively, finishing with 24 points, nine assists and six rebounds for the Shock, who tightened up their defense in the second half when they outscored the Monarchs 40-22. Cheryl Ford was in foul trouble much of the game and finished with five points and six rebounds.

"Detroit is a very good team, they just wear you down with their style of play and physicality," Monarchs coach Jenny Boucek said. "That's what they've built that team on. They are playing well right now, they are the real deal."

Nicole Powell scored 17 points and Crystal Kelly had 10 for Sacramento (2-4), which shot 63 percent in the first half when it led by four points.

But minus injured point guard Ticha Penicheiro all game and with limited duty from Adrian Williams-Strong, another injured starter, the Monarchs were outplayed badly in the second half.

"I knew they had been off a while [a week] and were mouthy, talking about how they wanted to beat the Shock," Laimbeer said. "We put them out two years ago in the finals, I know that sticks with them. We simply played better defense in the second half, that's all we talked about at halftime.

It was Smith's 3 with 2:01 left in the third quarter that put Detroit ahead for good at 57-54. A 16-10 advantage in the third period put the Shock in front 60-58 heading into the fourth.

Smith and Nolan connected on consecutive 3s early in the fourth quarter to extend the Shock's lead to 68-58.

"We let them get hot and that's the thing you can't do," Sacramento's Kara Lawson said. "If you let those two get going ... You saw how good they are, 54 points tonight."

Playing tough inside at the offensive end and forcing turnovers on defense, the Monarchs outscored Detroit 27-19 in the second quarter to take a 48-44 lead at the half. An 11-0 run put Sacramento ahead midway through the period.

"We stopped turning the ball over in the second half, which stopped their easy baskets," Smith said. "We also limited their penetration and rebounded a lot better than in the first half."

Smith got the Shock going early. She hit a pair of 3s and scored 15 points, helping Detroit take a 25-21 lead after one quarter.

Sacramento Kings players Ron Artest and Francisco Garcia watched the Monarchs lose their first home game of the season.

Arguing calls throughout the first three quarters, Laimbeer drew a technical early in the fourth following another outburst.

Penicheiro injured her left shoulder in practice this week.
